<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n43097b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n43" href="#n43097b">N43 (VI.B.35)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n43all.htm#n43097b"> 97(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> nose pinturos <font face="wake">}</font> / maguey plant / annaltes</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Matters of only passing importance were recorded <font color="green">[by the Mayans]</font> on fibrous paper made from the leaves of the maguey plant; &ldquo;records intended to be permanently kept were painted on the prepared skins of animals (&hellip;) These paintings or &lsquo;pinturos&rsquo; are usually executed on both sides of the skin, which was oblong in shape and often of great length, having the ends protected by boards&rdquo;. (&hellip;) These boards are called <i>analtees</i>, a word which may be translated <i>annals</i>. <small> Edward Clodd, <a name="ECSA2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ECSA2"><cite title="source">The Story of the Alphabet</cite></a>, rev. ed. (1913) 77 [Memory-aids and Picture-writing]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
